I agree, he’s not entirely wrong, but this response reveals the underlying mentality of our society. No matter how open-minded or educated people pretend to be, many still think this way. I’m shocked that someone in my own friend circle could say this. This society is truly sick.

I remember sharing an incident with a very close male friend about being molested while I was drunk. He initially showed sympathy, but then casually said, ‘Stop talking like a 12-year-old, it’s your responsibility to keep yourself safe.’

I’m in shock, struggling to accept that our society is still so broken, that our system is still so hollow. The perpetrators of such atrocities should face the harshest of punishments—enough to instill fear in anyone who might even consider such a vile act in the future.

I thought our system would improve, that such barbaric acts would become unthinkable out of sheer fear of punishment. But here we are, years later, facing the same nightmare. A young female doctor in Kolkata, brutally raped and murdered.

It’s heartbreaking to realize that when the Nirbhaya case happened, I was too young to fully grasp the depth of the horror, but even then, I knew it was beyond comprehension—a crime so heinous that I believed it would be a turning point.
